    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:acc981b2-56a1-4ee8-b219-e7eb9066737b",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 78-year-old retired mechanical engineer from Brno, Czech Republic. He is a tall, slightly stooped man with a broad silver moustache and a characteristically masked facial expression. His voice is noticeably soft and monotone. During the consultation he sits rigidly in his chair, his right hand displaying a visible pill-rolling resting tremor [MEDLINEPLUS:G20, SNOMED:G20]. He rises slowly from his seat and walks with short, shuffling steps, reduced arm swing on the right side, and occasional difficulty turning — a functional gait abnormality that his wife notes has worsened over the past two years [SNOMED:G20, MEDLINEPLUS:G20].\n\n{patientName} is a widower who lives with his adult daughter in a ground-floor flat adapted with grab rails. He was a keen chess player and amateur wood-carver, though he has had to abandon carving because of the trembling of his hands and the stiffness of his arms, legs and trunk [MEDLINEPLUS:G20]. He enjoys afternoon walks in the local park with his daughter, though these have become shorter and slower. He has a close circle of retired colleagues with whom he meets weekly for coffee.\n\nHe reports that symptoms began gradually about five years ago, initially only on his right side — a trembling of the right hand at rest — before spreading to affect both sides [MEDLINEPLUS:G20]. He also complains of slowness of movement (bradykinesia), poor balance and coordination, and increasing trouble with fine motor tasks such as buttoning his shirt [MEDLINEPLUS:G20]. Sleep is disrupted, and his daughter has noticed he sometimes acts out dreams. He has mild constipation and occasional difficulty swallowing [MEDLINEPLUS:G20]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5551d36a-7391-45f4-b49c-c2a6c68bd1ca",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was diagnosed with Parkinson's disease approximately three years ago following a neurological assessment prompted by progressive right-sided resting tremor and bradykinesia that had been worsening for two years [MEDLINEPLUS:G20]. A DaTscan at the time of diagnosis demonstrated reduced dopamine transporter uptake in the bilateral striatum, consistent with PD [PMID:40021571]. He was commenced on levodopa with good initial motor response.\n\nComorbidities include hypertension (managed with amlodipine) and osteoarthritis of the right hip, for which he underwent a right hip replacement in 2017. He has a history of mild depression, for which duloxetine was briefly trialled by his general practitioner two years ago; however, this was discontinued after it worsened his motor symptoms — a well-recognised phenomenon of duloxetine unmasking or exacerbating parkinsonism [PMID:40021571]. He has since been managed for depressive symptoms non-pharmacologically.\n\n{patientName} is a non-smoker and drinks one glass of wine with dinner approximately twice a week. He was a mechanical engineer for 35 years and retired at 65. He has no history of significant environmental toxin exposure. He has a documented penicillin allergy (urticaria). His daughter accompanies him to all neurology appointments and assists with medication administration."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
